We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to:
Reverse the accounting entry made in adjusting the PPE account balances;
Provide details on the reconciliation and/or reclassification of accounts in order to determine which specific PPE accounts have to be written-off/derecognized;
Submit the request for authority to derecognize/write-off non-existing PPEs substantially supported with the required documents under COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended that Management require:
The Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit the JEV to reclassify from the PPE accounts to appropriate inventory accounts the small tangible items costing less than ₱15,000, and recognize expense upon issuance thereof to end-users;
The General Services Office to maintain a separate inventory report and records for these items in order to monitor the issuance thereof and accountability thereon.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:

a.	 Fast track the completion of application for LBP’s “We Access” services for online viewing of bank accounts;

b.	 Pending the completion of the application for “We Access” services, request for snap-shot statements from the bank/s to facilitate prompt bank reconciliation process;

c.	 As directed thru Memorandum dated August 14, 2020 (per management’s reply to last year’s audit finding), prepare the List of Outstanding Checks showing essential details such as check number, date of check, payee, amount and brief description of the transaction in order to properly facilitate the identification of stale checks and appropriate adjustment thereof in the books;

d.	 Make representation with the bank/s to obtain copies of bank credit or debit memos in order to identify the nature of the transaction/s and other necessary details for proper treatment thereof in the books;

e.	 Immediately take up all other valid reconciling items presented in the BRS as adjustments in the books; and

f.	 Thereafter, ensure timely preparation and submission of the monthly BRS in compliance with COA Circular No. 96-011 and immediate adjustment to appropriate accounts of all reconciling items identified therein.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant in coordination with the Human Resource Unit to: 

a.	 Evaluate / assess the Accounting Unit’s current manpower and the personnel’s individual capacity / capability whether it is sufficient and qualified enough to cater to the demands of the unit particularly in the preparation and timely submission of accounts to COA;

b.	 Based on the results of the assessment, make and/or suggest necessary adjustments in the delegation of tasks to the concerned personnel or in the unit’s composition, if deemed necessary;  

c.	 Submit immediately all disbursement vouchers, official receipts and supporting documents as well as the trial balances and related reports covering the period March to December 2020; and

d.	 Thereafter, ensure prompt submission of accounts to COA pursuant to pertinent laws, rules and regulations mentioned herein.

We recommended that Management require the Accounting Unit to:

a.	 Ensure that withholding taxes are deducted from payments of honoraria in accordance with the Revised Withholding Tax Table as prescribed under Annex A of BIR Revenue Memorandum Circular No. 105-2017 dated December 28, 2017, and ensure that the same are remitted to the BIR within the prescribed period;

b.	 Submit additional NoA and other documentary requirements for successfully completed procurement projects (through competitive bidding only), if any, and ensure thereafter that payments of honoraria are within the maximum allowable rates pursuant to Item 5.3 of the aforementioned DBM Circular;

c.	 Submit proof and authority that the 2 JO personnel performed their duties beyond the regular office hours to support payment of their overtime services; and

d.	 Submit the lacking documentary requirements to support payment of honoraria of the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) and other LGU personnel involved in procurement.

