We recommended that Management allocate sufficient funds for this purpose and:
Fast track the submission of the Solid Waste Management Plan to the DENR for final approval by the National Solid Waste Management Commission;
Cease the operation of the illegal open dumpsite and scout a land suitable for sanitary landfill;
Intensify awareness of  proper waste segregation and strict implementation of best practices that mitigates air and water pollution through passage of municipal ordinance;
Educate its people, particularly farmers, for the production of organic fertilizers sourced from agricultural wastes  in coordination with the  Department of Agriculture for funding and technical assistance, and
The Municipal Solid Waste Management Board to closely monitor the compliance and implementation of the provisions under RA 9003.

We recommended that Management:
Create and establish the Municipal Council for the Protection of Children (MCPC) by issuing an Office Order copy furnished the COA Auditor;
Enjoin its MCPC to actively participate in the planning, implementation and monitoring of its projects, programs and activities to identify and resolve issues and problems on children in their locality;
Observe the activities to be performed by the MCPC as provided under Item B of DILG Memorandum Circular 2005-007 and  Item II of DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2012-120. and to
Submit the annual Accomplishment Report/ utilization report of the budget allocated for the activities of the MCPC, copy furnished the COA Auditor.

We recommended that Management require the Acting Municipal Accountant to:
Strictly adhere to the prescribed time frame for the submission of monthly accounts and financial reports to the Office of the Auditor not later than the 20th day after the end of each month as prescribed under Section 70 of the NGAS Manual;
Likewise, turn over the receipts and disbursement records with all paid vouchers and journals evidencing the transaction to the Auditor within 10 days of the ensuing month in compliance with Section 7.2.1(a) of COA Circular No. 2009-006.

We recommended that Management require the following:
Municipal DRRM Officer to ensure that the planned disaster-related activities and programs are implemented within the year;
Municipal Treasurer and Accountant to revert/transfer back to the General Fund, the unexpended DRRM – Capital Outlay portion erroneously transferred to the Trust Liabilities – DRMM under the Trust Fund.

We recommended to require the following:

That  the Municipal Mayor should create an inventory committee of three (3) as provided under Section 156 of COA Circular 92-386 to conduct physical count of properties to include those acquired or donated land and those funded from outside sources and require the committee to render the required physical inventory report by type to be submitted to the LCE copy furnished the Office of the Auditor;

Ensure that all department office head should be required to conduct its own physical count of all properties in their respective department/office based on the MRs and AREs on file at their office and to submit the RPCPPE and Inspection and Inventory of Unserviceable Property(IIRUP), if applicable;

Prepare a separate report for loss of property to the Committee, copy furnished the Auditor’s Office;

Accordingly, reconcile the balances appearing in the inventory report  with the subsidiary ledger records of the accounting to the general ledger so that total valuation of properties appearing in the Trial Balance could be validated as to its correctness and accuracy;

Real property cards shall be maintained by the General Service Office Designate  and on each of the Property Plant and Equipment account in order to come up with realistic data of property inventory account;

The semi-expendable items shall be separately reported as Inventory Supplies; and

The book value of the properties as well as the status or condition of the properties shall also be indicated in the report.

Recommendation:
We recommended that the Management of LGU-Initao  require the following:
Create an inventory committee composed of three (3) members as provided under Section 156 of COA Circular 92-386 to conduct physical count of properties to include those acquired or donated land and those funded from outside sources and require the committee to render the required physical inventory report by type to be submitted to the LCE, copy furnished the Office of the Auditor;
Ensure that all department office heads shall be required to conduct its own physical count of all properties in their respective department/office based on the MRs and AREs on file at their office and to submit the RPCPPE and Inspection and Inventory of Unserviceable Property(IIRUP), if applicable;
Prepare a separate report for loss of property to the Committee, copy furnished the Auditor’s Office;
Accordingly, reconcile the balances appearing in the inventory report/ RPCPPE with the subsidiary ledger and the general ledger records of Accounting Office  so that  the total valuation of properties appearing in the Trial Balance could be validated as to its correctness and accuracy;
Real property cards shall be maintained by the General Service Office Designate  and on each of the Property Plant and Equipment account in order to come up with realistic data of property inventory account;
The semi-expendable items shall be separately reported as Inventory Supplies; and
The book value of the properties as well as the status or condition of the properties shall also be indicated in the report.

Recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Accountant-Designate submit the monthly accounts and financial reports to the Office of the Auditor not later than the 20th day after the end of each month in accordance with Section 70 of the NGAS Manual.  Likewise, submit the receipts and disbursement records with all paid vouchers and documents evidencing the transaction to the Auditor within ten (10) days of the ensuing month in compliance with Section 7.2.1(a) of COA Circular No. 2009-006;
Also, require the Municipal Accountant-Designate to closely coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer for the latter to submit immediately the required reports within the prescribed period, and to facilitate the recording of the transactions in the books of accounts.

We have recommended the following:

That the Municipal Accounting Department should include in their priority activities for Calendar Year 2015 the preparation of Bank Reconciliation Statements, at the same time maintain up-to-date preparation of the same statements onwards.

Adhere to the provisions of paragraph 3.2 of COA Circular No. 96-011 dated October 2, 1996;

Monitor the timely submission of the required reports and instruct the concerned employees to give top priority in providing the team with BRS which were not yet submitted to avoid delay in the audit and verification of said reports;

 Likewise, exercise due diligence in the supervision and monitoring of the workload and accomplishment of the personnel assigned in the preparation of financial reports particularly the BRS to avoid repetitive audit observations.

We recommended to require the Municipal Accountant-Designate to   strictly adhere to the prescribed time frame for the submission of monthly accounts and financial reports to the Office of the Auditor not later than the 20th day after the end of each month as prescribed under Section 70 of the NGAS Manual.  Likewise, turn over the receipts and disbursement records with all paid vouchers and documents evidencing the transaction to the Auditor within 10 days of the ensuing month in compliance of Section 7.2.1(a) of COA Circular No. 2009-006;

Also, require the Municipal Accountant-Designate to closely coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer for the latter to submit immediately the required reports within the prescribed period, and to facilitate the recording of the transactions in the books of accounts.

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to pay only disbursement vouchers with complete documentations pursuant to Section 4(6) of PD 1445 which provides that claims against government funds shall be supported with complete documentation, otherwise, these should not be valid and legal disbursements against the funds of the municipality.
